title A macOS key-card generator, Rish-orchestrated with audits, and Keaton's verified personal cards
prompt Keaton asked to silo and template-ify the two veganreyklah2 key-card PNGs with instructions, a plain white/black background-and-text palette, and macOS-compatible generation scripts that work within ai-jail and fit the getting-started/SOURCE docs in the generic Acme Corporation employee Radiant theme; then to create personal versions for Keaton Dunsford / keatondun@gmail.com / xykj61 matching the new SSH and GPG fingerprints, with the scripting done in Rishi and audits confirming the earlier key generation and the QR PNG generation are correct.
think Audited the host before building: the PUBKEYS.md fingerprints match the real keys on this machine exactly — Codeberg SSH SHA256:/zQD+..., GitHub SSH SHA256:fL9I..., OpenPGP 16226BC7...B8451F67 all confirmed via ssh-keygen -lf and gpg --fingerprint. So the earlier key generation is correct, and the cards can be trusted to carry true fingerprints.
think Chose the macOS tooling pragmatically: magick and fc-match are present; qrencode was not, and the vendored gratitude/libqrencode submodule is uninitialized, so building from source (the Linux script's path) would not work here. Installed qrencode via Homebrew (a tiny standard package) rather than fight the empty submodule — the user explicitly wanted working macOS QR generation. Wrote tools/make_key_card_macos.sh as the macOS sibling to the Linux make-key-card.sh: Homebrew qrencode + magick, a plain white-on-black-safe default palette, and a monospace font-resolution chain that accepts a family only when fontconfig actually returns it (fc-match never fails, so a bare request for Fira Code silently falls back to proportional Verdana — guarded against by checking the resolved family name), landing on Menlo, which ships on every Mac.
think Put the orchestration in Rish as asked, with real audits on both sides: tools/make_key_card.rish runs a pre-audit (each declared fingerprint must match the real key on the host, or it refuses to render a misleading card), generates the cards, then a post-audit (the output PNGs must exist and be correctly shaped). The ssh-keygen/gpg/magick reads and config sourcing live behind a .sh seam (tools/key_card_audit.sh) per the project's own .sh/.rish boundary; Rish owns the order, the assertions, and the go/no-go. Green run = fingerprints verified AND images valid, not merely a command that ran.
think Generated Keaton's personal cards and verified them independently: keys_menlo_xykj61_{landscape,portrait}.png rendered green through the Rish orchestrator, and I decoded the three QR codes with zbar — each scans back byte-identical to the printed fingerprint and to what ssh-keygen/gpg reported. Also looked at the rendered card image directly to confirm the layout (diamond, name, handle, email, three labelled QR+text blocks, footer) is clean in the plain palette.
think Removed the stale veganreyklah2 cards rather than keep them: decoded them first and confirmed they carry entirely different fingerprints (the retired identity's old keys, 2nVRCdyz/i2QMVhai/0646 2132...), not the current xykj61 identity — so they were genuinely superseded, and the reframe/identity transition means the retired-handle cards no longer represent anyone current. git rm'd both.
think Template-ified for the generic Acme employee: tools/key-card.conf.example gained the plain-palette default, the optional audit-input fields (KEY_SSH_*, GPG_EMAIL), and pointers to all four scripts; wrote manual/guides/key-cards-setup.md in Radiant generic-Acme voice (what a card is, how to gather fingerprints, fill the config, generate on macOS or Linux, verify with zbar, do it inside the enclosure, troubleshoot); and updated SOURCE.md's Step to offer the macOS Rish path first, the plain palette, and the new generic guide. Keaton's own tools/key-card.conf stays gitignored.
obs The audit chain is the real deliverable, not just the images: a card literally cannot ship a wrong fingerprint now, because the Rish orchestrator refuses to render until every declared fingerprint matches the real key on the host, and the QR round-trip was independently confirmed with zbar. The plain white/black palette also makes the card print- and scan-robust in a way the old warm-orange one was not.
file tools/make_key_card_macos.sh why: macOS card generator — Homebrew qrencode + magick, plain palette, Menlo fallback
file tools/make_key_card.rish why: Rish orchestrator — pre-audit fingerprints, generate, post-audit PNGs
file tools/key_card_audit.sh why: the fingerprint + PNG audit seam (ssh-keygen/gpg/magick reads)
file tools/key-card.conf.example why: template-ified with plain palette + audit inputs + all-script pointers
file manual/guides/key-cards-setup.md why: generic Acme-voice walkthrough, macOS + Linux, with zbar verification
file SOURCE.md why: Step now offers the macOS Rish path first, plain palette, links the new guide
file keys_menlo_xykj61_landscape.png why: Keaton's verified personal card (landscape), fingerprints QR-decode-confirmed
file keys_menlo_xykj61_portrait.png why: Keaton's verified personal card (portrait)
file work-in-progress/TASKS.md why: key-card generator + Ojjo marked done in the downstream thread
recommend keep-going — the card chain is witnessed (fingerprints audited, QR round-trip confirmed); Fira Code is the only cosmetic gap (Menlo used), installable if its look is wanted.
